ult education policy -- tAdult basic education in Australia: in need of a new song sheet? -- tTransnational perspectives -- tEducation policy and the European Semester: challenging soft power in hard times -- tRethinking adult education for active participatory citizenship and resistance in Europe -- tLeaving no one behind: bringing equity and inclusion back into education -- tAfterword: resources of hope -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNeoliberalism has been widely criticised because of its role in prioritising ‘free markets’ as the optimum way of solving problems and organising society. In the field of education, this leads to an emphasis on the knowledge economy that can reduce both persons and education to economic actors and be detrimental to wider social and ethical goals. Drawing on a range of international contexts across informal, adult, school and university settings, this book provides innovative examples that show how neoliberalism in education can be challenged and changed at the local, national and transnational levels in order to foster a more democratic culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aEducationxPhilosophy. 0aNeoliberalism. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aAllatt, Gwyneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBates, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Zhe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCort, Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Shiv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuckworth, Vicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc